belonged to a party.

32:41.867 --> 32:43.133 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
It doesn't.

32:43.133 --> 32:45.533 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
As if it belonged to
an ideological wing.

32:45.533 --> 32:46.533 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
It doesn't.

32:46.533 --> 32:48.033 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
SEN.

32:48.033 --> 32:49.533 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
LINDSEY GRAHAM: Well, here's
what I say about originalism.

32:49.533 --> 32:51.600 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Whether you like it or not,
is it bound by the law?

32:51.600 --> 32:53.133 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
NEIL GORSUCH: Of course it is.

32:53.133 --> 32:55.300 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
It's the whole point of
how you interpret the law.

32:55.300 --> 32:57.367 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
SEN.

32:57.367 --> 33:00.267 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
LINDSEY GRAHAM: Now, to those
who believe the Constitution
is a living, breathing document

33:00.267 --> 33:04.133 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
that can speak to you and
nobody else, that bothers me.

33:04.133 --> 33:09.133 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The bottom line is, there are
different ways of looking at
the role of being a judge.

33:11.200 --> 33:14.733 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Do you believe that your way
of looking at being a judge
has stood the test of time?

33:17.733 --> 33:19.700 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
NEIL GORSUCH: I do.

33:19.700 --> 33:22.467 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: So, Marcia
Coyle, what did we learn
about Judge Gorsuch from this?

33:22.467 --> 33:24.533 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
MARCIA COYLE, "The
National Law Journal": OK.

33:24.533 --> 33:28.000 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Well, I think two things were
going on here in the exchange,
particularly with Senator

33:28.000 --> 33:30.000 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Feinstein.

33:30.000 --> 33:34.000 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
First of all, she was trying
to get at, what kind of
originalist is Judge Gorsuch?

33:34.867 --> 33:37.300 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
They're not all the same.

33:37.300 --> 33:40.033 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And, in fact, Justice Scalia,
who was a self-proclaimed
originalist, often said
that Justice Clarence

33:41.667 --> 33:44.500 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
Thomas was the only
true originalist on
the Supreme Court.

33:44.500 --> 33:49.500 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, she was trying to get
a sense of him and also her
concern about precedent.

33:51.400 --> 33:55.067 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I mean, it is true every Supreme
Court nominee has testified
to respect for precedent.

33:56.567 --> 34:00.533 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
But precedents, old
decisions, do get overruled.

34:00.533 --> 34:05.500 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The question was, what factors
do you use, can you justify
upsetting the law by overruling

34:06.133 --> 34:08.200 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
an old decision?

34:08.200 --> 34:12.467 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And Judge Gorsuch did lay out
the factors multiple times,
even though he won't commit

34:13.800 --> 34:17.267 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
to not overruling
a specific case.

34:17.267 --> 34:19.367 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Pam Karlan, what
did you take away from this?

34:19.367 --> 34:21.967 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
PAM KARLAN, Stanford
Law School: Well, here's
what was interesting.

34:21.967 --> 34:25.367 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
He did commit to not
overruling Brown against
Board Of Education.

34:25.367 --> 34:27.433 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
He said that case was
correctly decided.

34:27.433 --> 34:32.267 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
He did commit to not overturning
Griswold about the right
of married couples to use

34:32.267 --> 34:34.400 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
contraception.

34:34.400 --> 34:38.267 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But he refused to commit to
the same idea with regard to
cases like Roe or cases like

34:38.867 --> 34:40.967 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Lawrence.

34:40.967 --> 34:44.533 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
And there's no honest
originalist who really
can say that the people
who ratified the 14th

34:46.533 --> 34:49.533 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Amendment in 1868 thought
that it protected gay people,
given that the same people who

34:51.033 --> 34:55.100 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
ratified that amendment
all prohibited sodomy
in their states.

34:57.100 --> 35:00.900 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, I think he gave us a very
clear sense of what kind of
an originalist he was today

35:02.800 --> 35:04.533 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
in the way he answered
questions about different
lines of precedent.

35:04.533 --> 35:06.467 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Ilya Shapiro?

35:06.467 --> 35:07.833 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
ILYA SHAPIRO, Cato
Institute: Well, Pam, I'm
an honest originalist.

35:07.833 --> 35:09.900 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
At least I try to be.

35:09.900 --> 35:13.233 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And I would say that the
14th Amendment does protect
gay rights in various ways.

35:13.233 --> 35:17.700 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I filed briefs supporting
the challengers in Obergefell
and all the others.

35:17.700 --> 35:22.000 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The Cato Institute has long
been about that, because you
have to understand that you do

35:22.000 --> 35:24.167 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
originalism at the right time.

35:24.167 --> 35:28.400 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
You're not looking into
the brains, into minds
of the people that were
enacting it or ratifying

35:28.400 --> 35:29.400 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
it.

35:29.400 --> 35:30.600 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
You look at the words.

35:30.600 --> 35:32.767 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
And what did the words
mean at the time?

35:32.767 --> 35:36.567 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
Equal means equal, just
like you don't have to
update the Constitution
to apply the Interstate

35:38.567 --> 35:41.200 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Commerce Clause to airplanes
or the Internet, because
that's interstate commerce.

35:41.200 --> 35:43.267 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(CROSSTALK)

35:43.267 --> 35:45.233 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Amy Howe,
I'm going to come to you to
ask you to adjudicate this.

35:45.233 --> 35:47.300 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(LAUGHTER)

35:47.300 --> 35:50.233 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
AMY HOWE, SCOTUSblog.com: Well,
I think that this is really
sort of a bigger picture issue,

35:50.233 --> 35:55.233 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
which is that the senators,
the Democrats senators, are
trying to get more information

35:55.833 --> 35:57.867 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
about Gorsuch.

35:57.867 --> 36:01.600 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And, you know, Donald Trump
said he wanted to appoint
justices in the mold of Scalia

36:02.633 --> 36:04.800 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
and Clarence Thomas.

36:04.800 --> 36:07.767 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And the Democratic senators
are trying to figure out,
well, you know, what makes him

36:07.767 --> 36:09.833 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
think that?

36:09.833 --> 36:13.133 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
You know, OK, and there's
originalism, but what kind of
originalism -- originalist are

36:13.133 --> 36:15.233 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
you?

36:15.233 --> 36:17.233 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: All right,
there's something else I
want you all to listen to.

36:17.233 --> 36:20.667 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
During his campaign, we know
that then-candidate Donald Trump
promised to appoint justices

36:22.567 --> 36:25.433 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
with similar philosophies
to himself and to
Justice Antonin Scalia.

36:25.433 --> 36:30.433 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
Now, Democratic Senator
Patrick Leahy questioned
- - today questioned
Judge Gorsuch on where

36:31.033 --> 36:31.567 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
his views are.

36:31.567 --> 36:33.633 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
SEN.

36:33.633 --> 36:36.633 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
PATRICK LEAHY (D), Vermont:
Mr. Priebus said you have the
vision of Donald Trump, and,

36:36.633 --> 36:41.633 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
by nominating you, Donald Trump
was talking about changing
potentially 40 years of law,

36:43.233 --> 36:48.233 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
suggesting you are coming
in as a Trojan horse.

36:49.400 --> 36:51.433 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
What vision do you share
with President Trump?

36:51.433 --> 36:56.133 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
NEIL GORSUCH: Senator, I mean,
no disrespect to any other
person in saying, they don't

36:57.367 --> 36:58.667 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
speak for me.

36:58.667 --> 37:00.867 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
And I don't speak for them.

37:00.867 --> 37:05.867 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
You know, I have great
admiration for Justice Scalia,
as we have talked about.

37:07.800 --> 37:10.933 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I have admiration for every
member of this committee and
for the president of the United

37:10.933 --> 37:13.400 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
States, for the vice president
of the United States.

37:13.400 --> 37:16.067 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
But, respectfully, none
of you speaks for me.

37:16.067 --> 37:18.200 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
I speak for me.

37:18.200 --> 37:19.900 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
I am a judge.

37:19.900 --> 37:21.433 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
I am independent.

37:21.433 --> 37:22.900 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
I make up my own mind.

37:22.900 --> 37:24.867 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
SEN.

37:24.867 --> 37:26.567 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
RICHARD DURBIN (D-IL), Minority
Whip: Judge, in eight out
of 10 cases that came before

37:26.567 --> 37:28.267 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
you, you ruled against the
students with disabilities.

37:28.267 --> 37:29.700 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(CROSSTALK)

37:29.700 --> 37:31.733 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
NEIL GORSUCH: I'm sure
they were unanimous panels.

37:31.733 --> 37:35.800 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And to suggest that I have
some animus against children,
Senator, would be mistaken.

37:39.433 --> 37:40.433 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
SEN.

37:40.433 --> 37:43.733 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
RICHARD DURBIN: Judge, please.

37:43.733 --> 37:45.800 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
I'm not suggesting that.

37:45.800 --> 37:50.033 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
You are -- what I'm basically
saying to you is, I can only
look at your court opinions,

37:52.367 --> 37:56.100 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the words you write,
because, like many nominees,
you are careful in your
testimony before us.

37:57.933 --> 38:00.800 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
You have told us time and again,
no place for my heart here.

38:00.800 --> 38:02.100 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
This is all about the facts.

38:02.100 --> 38:03.333 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
This is all about the law.

38:03.333 --> 38:05.300 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
I don't buy that.

38:05.300 --> 38:09.600 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I don't think that the decisions
of courts are so robotic,
so programmatic that all you

38:11.633 --> 38:13.867 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
need to do is to look at the
facts and look at the law and
there's an obvious conclusion.

38:13.867 --> 38:16.033 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
If that were the case, there
would never be a dissent.

38:16.033 --> 38:19.667 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Amy
Howe, do we -- what do
we take away from this?

38:19.667 --> 38:24.667 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
This was about whether
Judge Gorsuch sees people
as human beings, or is
he blindly following

38:25.967 --> 38:27.967 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
the law, it seemed?

38:27.967 --> 38:29.967 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
AMY HOWE: Well, what I would
say, I think maybe what Durbin
was trying to say -- and

38:29.967 --> 38:34.100 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
maybe it was just inartfully
phrased -- is - - and he had
something there, the idea Judge

38:34.100 --> 38:35.900 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
Gorsuch keeps
saying, I'm a judge.

38:35.900 --> 38:38.067 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
I apply the laws to the facts.

38:38.067 --> 38:41.633 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But it's not always that
easy, particularly when you
get to the Supreme Court.

38:41.633 --> 38:44.700 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Cases get to the Supreme
Court because they're hard.

38:44.700 --> 38:49.700 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And as Senator Durbin said, if
it were that easy, a computer
could do it, there would

38:50.300 --> 38:52.267 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
be no dissents.

38:52.267 --> 38:55.533 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And so what he was, I think,
trying to get at was, you
know, like, when there's a gray

38:55.533 --> 38:57.367 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
area, what else are you
going to bring to the table?

38:57.367 --> 38:59.900 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
JUDY WOODRUFF: What do
you take away from all
this, Ilya Shapiro?

38:59.900 --> 39:04.633 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ILYA SHAPIRO: Well, I
look at it another couple
of changes during the
day's questioning with

39:06.467 --> 39:08.533 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Al Franken about arbitration,
and then with Ben Sasse
about the same topic.

39:08.533 --> 39:13.300 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And this goes towards how some
judges are simply more willing
to bend the law to achieve

39:13.300 --> 39:17.167 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
a just result, because,
otherwise, they don't like the
result that they're getting.

39:17.167 --> 39:21.000 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And Franken was talking about
how arbitration provisions
might go against the little guy.

39:21.000 --> 39:24.600 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And then Ben Sasse said, well,
I might agree with you in those
cases that you're presenting.

39:24.600 --> 39:28.300 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
So we, senators, the Congress,
should change those laws.

39:28.300 --> 39:30.367 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
And that's where the debate is.

39:30.367 --> 39:34.800 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Sometimes, just reaching a
result that seems unjust, that
is an indication for Congress

39:34.800 --> 39:36.033 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
to change it.

39:36.033 --> 39:38.033 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Pick up
on that, Pam Karlan.

39:38.033 --> 39:41.900 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
PAM KARLAN: Well, the question
is what the interpretation
of the Arbitration Act is.

39:41.900 --> 39:46.900 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The current Supreme Court,
with a Republican majority, has
narrowed people's ability to

39:48.967 --> 39:51.633 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
get into court by reading a
law that's been around since
the 1920s more narrowly than

39:51.633 --> 39:53.733 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
the court used to.

